    Copy-on-Write (COW) in Process Creation

    Copy-on-Write is a memory management technique used during process creation where the parent and child processes initially share the same memory pages. The operating system creates a separate copy of a memory page only when one of the processes modifies it. This improves performance and reduces memory usage.

        . Parent and child share the same memory pages
        . These pages are marked read-only
        . If either process tries to modify the memory, the OS creates a copy of that page

        So copying happens only when writing occurs.

    fork(), exec() & Vfork()

    fork() creates a new child process by duplicating the parent process. exec() replaces the current process with a new program without creating a new process. vfork() is similar to fork but allows the child process to share the parent's memory temporarily, making process creation faster.

