KASAN:
KASAN (Kernel Address Sanitizer) detects kernel memory errors by maintaining shadow memory for every 8 bytes of real memory. The compiler inserts runtime checks before memory accesses, and if an access touches poisoned memory (red zones or freed memory), KASAN reports the error along with the stack trace.

CONFIG_KASAN=y
CONFIG_KASAN_GENERIC=y

KASAN helps developers detect memory corruption bugs in the Linux kernel and kernel modules during runtime.

Common bugs it detects:

Use-after-free
Buffer overflow
Invalid pointer access
Out-of-bounds read/write

DMA:

DMA (Direct Memory Access) allows hardware devices to transfer data directly between the device and system memory without CPU intervention. In Linux kernel drivers, DMA is performed using APIs such as dma_alloc_coherent(), dma_map_single(), dma_unmap_single(), and dma_free_coherent(). The driver allocates DMA-capable memory, programs the device with the DMA address, and the device performs the transfer, notifying the CPU via interrupt when complete.

coharent DMA:

Memory allocated for coherent DMA is automatically kept cache-coherent between the CPU and the device. The CPU and device always see the same data without manual cache synchronization.

void *cpu_addr;
dma_addr_t dma_handle;

cpu_addr = dma_alloc_coherent(dev, size, &dma_handle, GFP_KERNEL);

cpu_addr → CPU virtual address
dma_handle → device DMA address

Streaming DMA:

Streaming DMA is used for temporary DMA transfers where the buffer is mainly used by either the CPU or the device at different times. Cache synchronization must be done manually.

dma_addr_t dma_handle;

dma_handle = dma_map_single(dev, cpu_buffer, size, DMA_TO_DEVICE);

/* device performs DMA */

dma_unmap_single(dev, dma_handle, size, DMA_TO_DEVICE);

If CPU needs to read data after DMA:

dma_sync_single_for_cpu(dev, dma_handle, size, DMA_FROM_DEVICE);

Page fault:

A page fault is an interrupt generated by the CPU when a program accesses a virtual memory page that is not currently mapped to physical memory.




